Aphid.description: Small soft-bodied insects that feed on plant sap, often forming colonies on shoots and leaves.

Ladybug.description: Rounded beetles with spots that prey on soft-bodied pests like aphids.

Caterpillar.description: Larval stage of butterflies and moths; many species feed heavily on leaves.

Beetle.description: Diverse order with many families; roles vary from pollinators to plant pests.

Grasshopper.description: Herbivorous orthopterans known for strong hind legs and crop feeding.

Spider.description: Arachnids that prey on insects; generally beneficial in agricultural contexts.

Ant.description: Social insects with varied ecological roles; some species can be agricultural pests.

Bee.description: Pollinating hymenopterans; essential for many crops; generally protected.

Butterfly.description: Adult lepidopterans with scaled wings; generally beneficial as pollinators.

Moth.description: Diverse lepidopterans; some species have larvae that damage crops.

Cutworm.description: Larvae of noctuid moths; feed at night and cut plants near soil surface causing stand loss.

Grub.description: C-shaped larvae of scarab beetles; feed on roots of grasses and crops leading to wilting and dead patches.

handling: remove hiding places and mulch moisture
Slug.description: Terrestrial mollusks; feed on foliage, seedlings, and fruit; activity increases with moisture and cool temperatures.
